                <td><span class="badge @(svc.Healthy ? "badge-healthy" : "badge-unhealthy")">@(svc.Healthy ? "Healthy" : "Unhealthy")</span></td>
                <td><code>@svc.ResponseTime</code></td>
            </tr>
        }
    </tbody>
</table>

<!-- ── What is FlowCore ── -->
<h2 class="section-title">What is FlowCore?</h2>
<div class="guide-section">
    <p>FlowCore is a <strong>proof-of-concept</strong> that validates whether a modern, cloud-native microservices architecture on <strong>Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS)</strong> can replace legacy monolithic systems. It was built from 14 detailed specification modules covering everything from infrastructure provisioning to cost management.</p>

    <div class="guide-highlight">
        <h3>The Stack</h3>
        <div class="tech-pills">
            <span class="pill">.NET 8</span>
            <span class="pill">C# Microservices</span>
            <span class="pill">Azure Kubernetes Service</span>
            <span class="pill">PostgreSQL</span>
            <span class="pill">Redis</span>
            <span class="pill">Azure Service Bus</span>
            <span class="pill">Key Vault</span>
            <span class="pill">Application Insights</span>
            <span class="pill">Bicep IaC</span>
            <span class="pill">GitHub Actions CI/CD</span>
            <span class="pill">YARP API Gateway</span>
            <span class="pill">Docker / ACR</span>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ── How It Works ── -->
<h2 class="section-title">How It Works — Step by Step</h2>
<div class="guide-steps">
    <div class="guide-step">
        <div class="guide-step-num">1</div>
        <div class="guide-step-body">
            <h3>Request Enters via API Gateway</h3>
            <p>All external traffic hits the <strong>YARP-based API Gateway</strong> — the single entry point for the entire system. It injects a <code>X-Correlation-ID</code> for end-to-end tracing, then routes the request to the appropriate backend service based on URL path (<code>/customers</code>, <code>/orders</code>, <code>/rules</code>, etc.).</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-step">
        <div class="guide-step-num">2</div>
        <div class="guide-step-body">
            <h3>Microservice Processes the Request</h3>
            <p>Each of the <strong>6 backend services</strong> owns exactly one business domain. The Customer Service manages profiles, Order Service handles transactions, Rules Service validates business logic, Reporting Service provides read views, Audit Service records events, and Cost Service tracks infrastructure spend. Each service has its <strong>own database schema</strong> — no shared writes.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-step">
        <div class="guide-step-num">3</div>
        <div class="guide-step-body">
            <h3>Events Published to Service Bus</h3>
            <p>When a domain action occurs (customer created, order placed), the service publishes an <strong>event to Azure Service Bus</strong> using pub-sub topics. Events include <code>CustomerUpdated</code>, <code>OrderPlaced</code>, <code>CaseCreated</code>, <code>NotificationRequested</code>, and <code>AuditRecorded</code>.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-step">
        <div class="guide-step-num">4</div>
        <div class="guide-step-body">
            <h3>Workers Consume Events Asynchronously</h3>
            <p>The <strong>Notification Worker</strong> runs in the workers namespace and subscribes to events via independent Service Bus subscriptions. Each subscription has retry policies (5 attempts, 1-min lock) and dead-letter queues for failed messages. The worker pool <strong>scales to zero</strong> when idle.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-step">
        <div class="guide-step-num">5</div>
        <div class="guide-step-body">
            <h3>Everything is Observable</h3>
            <p>Every service sends telemetry to <strong>Application Insights</strong>. Health checks (<code>/healthz</code>) are monitored by Kubernetes readiness and liveness probes. The correlation ID ties the entire request flow — from HTTP entry through Service Bus messages — into a single traceable transaction.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ── 7 Business Outcomes ── -->
<h2 class="section-title">7 Business Outcome Dimensions</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">Every technical decision traces back to one or more of these business drivers. This is what the POC validates.</p>
<div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card outcome-card">
        <div class="card-header"><span class="outcome-num">1</span> Modernization</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>Monolith &rarr; @Model.ServiceCount independent .NET 8 microservices. Each containerized with its own lifecycle. Infrastructure as Code via Bicep templates. No shared databases between services.</p>
            <div class="outcome-modules">Modules: A (Foundation), F (Core Services)</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card outcome-card">
        <div class="card-header"><span class="outcome-num">2</span> Cloud-Native Scalability</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>3 AKS node pools with autoscaling. Horizontal Pod Autoscalers on all services. Worker pool scales to zero. Redis caching for hot paths. Pods ready in &lt;60s.</p>
            <div class="outcome-modules">Modules: B (AKS Platform), C (Shared Services)</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card outcome-card">
        <div class="card-header"><span class="outcome-num">3</span> Delivery Acceleration</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>GitHub Actions CI/CD: contract validation (OpenAPI + AsyncAPI) &rarr; build &amp; test &rarr; ACR push &rarr; AKS deploy. Target: commit to production in &lt;10 minutes.</p>
            <div class="outcome-modules">Modules: J (CI/CD), C (ACR)</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card outcome-card">
        <div class="card-header"><span class="outcome-num">4</span> User Experience</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>API-first design with YARP Gateway. OpenAPI 3.0.3 contracts for all services. Stateless REST APIs — any frontend (web, mobile, CLI) can integrate.</p>
            <div class="outcome-modules">Module: F (API Gateway)</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card outcome-card">
        <div class="card-header"><span class="outcome-num">5</span> Cost Optimization</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>Burstable SKUs, scale-to-zero workers, environment lifecycle scripts (scale-down/up/teardown). ~60% savings during off-hours. <a href="/costs">View cost breakdown &rarr;</a></p>
            <div class="outcome-modules">Modules: A-E (Infrastructure), M (Cost Management)</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card outcome-card">
        <div class="card-header"><span class="outcome-num">6</span> Architectural Standardization</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>4-layer decomposition: Gateway &rarr; Services &rarr; Data &rarr; Integration. Schema-per-service isolation. Contract-first. Observable-by-default. <a href="/architecture">View architecture &rarr;</a></p>
            <div class="outcome-modules">Modules: D (Data), E (Messaging), F (Services)</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card outcome-card">
        <div class="card-header"><span class="outcome-num">7</span> Integration Modernization</div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>Azure Service Bus pub-sub replacing batch/FTP. Event-driven with dead-letter queues. Correlation ID tracking across all sync and async flows. <a href="/demo">Try live demo &rarr;</a></p>
            <div class="outcome-modules">Modules: E (Messaging), G (Workers)</div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ── Spec Modules ── -->
<h2 class="section-title">14 Specification Modules</h2>
<p style="color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">The entire system was built from these detailed specs. Each module covers a specific concern area.</p>
<div class="modules-grid">
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">0</span> Business Outcomes &amp; Drivers</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">A</span> Foundation &amp; Networking (VNet, Bicep)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">B</span> AKS Platform (Cluster, Node Pools)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">C</span> Shared Services (ACR, Redis, Key Vault)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">D</span> Data Layer (PostgreSQL, Schema Isolation)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">E</span> Messaging (Service Bus, Topics, Subs)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">F</span> Core Services (6 Microservices + Gateway)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">G</span> Workers (Notification, Background Processing)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">H</span> Observability (App Insights, Logging)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">I</span> Security (Network Policies, RBAC)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">J</span> CI/CD (GitHub Actions Pipelines)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">K</span> Resiliency (Failure Scenarios, PDBs)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">L</span> Exit Criteria (Success Metrics)</div>
    <div class="module-item"><span class="module-tag">M</span> Cost Management (Pricing, Advisor)</div>
</div>

